      Insider trading?
   =20
 =20
If your brother-in-law is a senior accounting executive at a public company=
, and that public company is secretly in negotiations to be acquired at a p=
remium, and your brother-in-law is working on the deal, and you talk to him=
=C2=A0regularly=C2=A0while the deal is being negotiated, =E2=80=9Cincluding=
 by phone, at [your] daughters=E2=80=99 basketball events, and at multiple =
family gatherings over the Christmas holidays,=E2=80=9D and after each time=
 you talk to him you buy some short-dated out-of-the-money call options on =
his company=E2=80=99s stock, and you call your son and tell=C2=A0him=C2=A0t=
o buy call options on the company=E2=80=99s stock, and you=C2=A0take out a =
loan on your car to buy even more call options on the company=E2=80=99s sto=
ck, and you make up 100% of the volume in those call options on some of the=
 days you trade, and then shortly after Christmas the company announces the=
 merger and the stock shoots up and you (and your son) make a ton of money =
on your call options=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0is that illegal insider trading?I =
don=E2=80=99t know! It has the main hallmarks of insider trading:=09Short-d=
ated out-of-the-money call options on a merger target, and=09Brothers-in-la=
w. (=E2=80=9CThe brother-in-law=E2=80=99s role=E2=80=9D in American culture=
, I once wrote, =E2=80=9Cis to insider trade on his brother-in-law=E2=80=99=
s information.=E2=80=9D)But notice that, in my litany of suspicious events,=
 I did not actually say =E2=80=9Cand your brother-in-law told you about the=
 merger negotiations.=E2=80=9D Sure he was working on the merger, and sure =
he kept seeing you at basketball events etc., and sure each time you saw hi=
m you went out and bought call options. But maybe you just talked about bas=
ketball! Maybe seeing him reminded you that his company existed, and you we=
nt off and did fundamental research and traded without any inside informati=
on from him. Or maybe you saw him looking stressed, or happy, or he rushed =
in late to basketball practice, and you thought =E2=80=9Chmm something migh=
t be cooking at his work=E2=80=9D and bought options without a tip from him=
.[1]Still, given that list of suspicious signs, it=E2=80=99s a safe bet tha=
t the Securities and Exchange Commission will bring an insider trading case=
. And in fact it did: This is a real case, the person who traded is Christo=
pher Clark (who made $243,000 of profits; his son made $53,000), and his br=
other-in-law is William Wright, an accounting officer at CEB Inc., which wa=
s acquired in 2017. The SEC sued last December. Last month, Wright settled=
=C2=A0without admitting or denying the charges, agreeing to pay a fine of a=
bout $240,000 and to be barred from serving as a director or officer of a p=
ublic company for two years. But Clark went to trial, and this week he won:=
A federal judge in northern Virginia on Monday dismissed the civil fraud ca=
se against Christopher J. Clark, whose bullish and risky trades just before=
 a 2017 acquisition were spotted by regulators=E2=80=99 high-powered survei=
llance databases. The SEC alleged Mr. Clark=E2=80=99s brother-in-law, a for=
mer corporate accounting officer, told him days before the deal that Gartne=
r Inc. would buy CEB Inc.U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton dismissed the SE=
C=E2=80=99s claims after regulators presented their evidence and before the=
 case was sent to the jury. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s just simply no circums=
tantial evidence here that gives rise to an inference that he received the =
insider information,=E2=80=9D Judge Hilton said Monday, according to a tran=
script. =E2=80=A6Mark Cummings, a lawyer for Mr. Clark, said the outcome un=
derscores that regulators can rely too much on statistical evidence, such a=
s trades made just before an event that caused a company=E2=80=99s stock pr=
ice to rise or fall. Data alone isn=E2=80=99t sufficient to support a civil=
 or criminal case against a trader, he said.Mr. Clark, 53 years old, refuse=
d to settle the SEC=E2=80=99s lawsuit because he had good reasons for belie=
ving CEB shares would rise, Mr. Cummings said. His research had nothing to =
do with his brother-in-law, William Wright, who had worked as CEB=E2=80=99s=
 corporate controller.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe lesson here is suspicious trading =
is not necessarily illegal trading,=E2=80=9D Mr. Cummings said. =E2=80=9CJu=
st because the circumstances look bad, there can be an equally innocent rea=
son for the activity.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CThe government can specula=
te that he made a little too much money, he was a little too successful or =
more successful than he ought to be, so therefore he=E2=80=99s getting insi=
der information,=E2=80=9D Judge Hilton said, according to the hearing trans=
cript. =E2=80=9CBut there=E2=80=99s no evidence of it.=E2=80=9DNotice that =
what happened here is=C2=A0not=C2=A0that the SEC presented all its suspicio=
us evidence, Clark testified =E2=80=9Cno I did my own research and it=E2=80=
=99s all innocent,=E2=80=9D and the=C2=A0jury went and deliberated and deci=
ded that they believed him. Instead, what happened here is that the SEC pre=
sented all of its suspicious evidence and the judge said =E2=80=9Cnope, the=
re=E2=80=99s nothing here even worth bothering a jury with.=E2=80=9D[2] Bel=
ieving Clark=E2=80=99s explanation has nothing to do with it; he didn=E2=80=
=99t even present his explanation. The judge just decided that the facts I =
laid out in my first paragraph=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0brothers-in-law, basketb=
all games, mergers, short-dated out-of-the-money call options =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0couldn=E2=80=99t possibly be=C2=A0enough, on their own, to find someone =
liable for insider trading.=C2=A0That will make life harder for the SEC! Th=
is is just one district judge=E2=80=99s decision in one case, and I would n=
ot exactly call it The Law, and in any case nothing in this column is ever =
legal advice, but I will say, if you find yourself in the fact pattern in t=
hat first paragraph =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you have been trading short-dated out=
-of-the-money call options on a merger target after seeing your brother-in-=
law who is working on the merger =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the SEC comes after you=
 for insider trading, don=E2=80=99t give up hope. =E2=80=9CWhat, all of thi=
s is nothing,=E2=80=9D you can say to the SEC, and to a judge, and if nobod=
y has any proof of what you talked about it might work.Also I can=E2=80=99t=
 believe Wright settled and has to pay the SEC $240,000.=C2=A0He=C2=A0didn=
=E2=80=99t make that money trading call options; Clark did, and Clark beat =
the charges. I know what Clark should give his brother-in-law for Christmas=
 this year.
