      SPARC SPARC SPARC
   =20
 =20
A share of a SPAC, a special purpose acquisition company, initially represe=
nts:=09A claim on $10 in a bank account, plus=09The right to pay that $10 t=
o buy a share of some company to be named later.The median value of Item 2,=
 these days, is roughly zero, so a lot of SPACs trade like claims on $10. (=
For time-value, liquidity, etc., reasons, this means that they trade at lik=
e $9.97.) But sometimes Item 2 is more valuable. If a SPAC has a good spons=
or with a good track record of finding good companies and negotiating good =
deals with them, then the SPAC=E2=80=99s shares should trade at, you know, =
$12 or $13. If the SPAC is rumored to be in negotiations with a very hot el=
ectric-vehicle company then it might trade at $50 or more, as  the SPAC tha=
t bought Lucid Group Inc. did right before the deal was announced.We have  =
talked a few  times=C2=A0about  Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s proposal to do a SPAR=
C, a special purpose acquisition=C2=A0rights=C2=A0company. A SPARC is like =
a SPAC except that instead of paying $10 for a share of a SPAC, you pay $0 =
for a =E2=80=9Cright=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwarrant=E2=80=9D of the SPARC.[3]=
 A SPARC warrant initially represents:=09The right to pay $10 to buy a shar=
e of some company to be named later.[4]That is, the SPARC consists of (1) a=
 SPAC=C2=A0minus=C2=A0(2) $10. In a SPAC, you put $10 in a pot and might la=
ter be asked to use it to buy a company, but you can say no and take your m=
oney back.=C2=A0In a SPARC, you might later be asked to put in $10 to buy a=
 company, but you can say no and keep your money.If you are very tidy-minde=
d, as I am, you will be tempted to say =E2=80=9Cwell this is exactly the sa=
me as a SPAC, except minus $10.=E2=80=9D Ten dollars is, as a financial qua=
ntity goes, quite straightforward and tractable. You can probably figure ou=
t how to subtract $10. In general, if I said to you =E2=80=9CAsset X is wor=
th an amount of money that depends on a complex formula and a series of ass=
umptions about cash flows and market psychology and managerial prowess, and=
 Asset Y is worth the same as Asset X minus $10,=E2=80=9D you would not thi=
nk that Asset Y is any=C2=A0harder=C2=A0to value than Asset X. If you can d=
o X, you can do Y. That subtraction is easy. Taking out the $10 makes no th=
eoretical difference.But much of the work of finance consists of doing thin=
gs that make no theoretical difference because they have some practical adv=
antage, and Ackman is very keen on his SPARC idea. (I am too; I think it=E2=
=80=99s fun.) A big advantage of the SPARC is that, if you=E2=80=99re a SPA=
RC investor,=C2=A0you get to keep your money:=C2=A0You only put up the $10 =
when Ackman finds a company to buy, rather than putting it in a pot while h=
e looks for one. There are also legal advantages that make the SPARC a bit =
more flexible than a SPAC: Ackman would have more time to find a company, a=
nd he=E2=80=99d be able to raise a variable amount of money with the SPARC =
rather than just the fixed amount in a SPAC pool.Also it seems to me that t=
he SPARC is in an important sense  more honest than a SPAC. The way a SPAC =
works is that it has some money in its pool, and the SPAC sponsor goes to a=
 private company and says =E2=80=9Chey I can take you public and give you t=
his $300 million=E2=80=9D or whatever, and they agree on a deal, and then t=
hey announce it, and then the SPAC shareholders can withdraw their money if=
 they want and the target company might get nothing. (See, e.g., BuzzFeed I=
nc.) The way a SPARC works is that Bill Ackman goes to a private company an=
d says =E2=80=9Chey I think if we play our cards right I can take you publi=
c and raise $3 billion for you=E2=80=9D or whatever, and if they agree on a=
 deal it=E2=80=99s because the company believes in Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s ab=
ility to raise the money, not because the company is distracted by the mone=
y already being there. In a SPAC the money is already there, but that=E2=80=
=99s an illusion; it can vanish. In a SPARC it is clearer that the money wi=
ll come only if the deal is good and Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s fans believe in =
it.On the other hand you might object that subtracting $10 from a SPAC make=
s the SPARC=C2=A0worse=C2=A0in some substantive way. In particular, these d=
ays, there are a lot of SPACs chasing not that many deals, a lot of SPAC in=
vestors ask for their money back when deals are announced, and so a lot of =
SPACs trade at around $10 or a little less =E2=80=94=C2=A0$9.97 or whatever=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0because they are effectively a weird way to get back $10 in=
 a few months. In other words, the right to buy a share of a stock to be na=
med later is worthless, and the SPAC share consists=C2=A0only=C2=A0of the c=
laim on $10.How does that work with a SPARC? The right can=E2=80=99t trade=
=C2=A0below=C2=A0zero, and even trading=C2=A0at=C2=A0zero =E2=80=94=C2=A0fo=
r a SPARC actively looking for a company =E2=80=94=C2=A0would be weird; sur=
ely there is=C2=A0some=C2=A0option value there. Maybe it=E2=80=99s worth a =
penny or two. But =E2=80=9Cmaybe a penny or two=E2=80=9D is a pretty bad pr=
ice for a publicly traded security, much much worse than =E2=80=9Cmaybe 10 =
bucks more or less.=E2=80=9D Subtracting $10 from the SPAC price, if the SP=
AC price is roughly $10, results in madness.Ackman and the New York Stock E=
xchange (which wants to list his SPARC) need the Securities and Exchange Co=
mmission to approve the idea, and the SEC seems unhappy. Michelle Celarier =
reports:The Securities and Exchange Commission is pushing back against hedg=
e fund manager Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s effort to create a new-fangled securit=
y called a SPARC, or special purpose acquisition rights company. =E2=80=A6I=
nstead of either approving the security or turning it down as expected, how=
ever, the SEC asked for more time =E2=80=94 and more information =E2=80=94 =
before making its decision. In a 17-page release, the regulator said that i=
t is worried about the new security=E2=80=99s potential for manipulation in=
 part because of comment letters it received from three people, one of whom=
 was anonymous. The vast majority of the comments on the new security, whic=
h was put forth by the New York Stock Exchange, were supportive. But the SE=
C is asking for more details from the NYSE on how its concerns will be addr=
essed.=C2=A0Here is the SEC=E2=80=99s response; here=E2=80=99s the section =
on the trading prices:The Exchange does not explain how market participants=
 would effectively value this novel listed security, or how it would be exp=
ected to trade consistent with fair and orderly markets and the protection =
of investors and the public interest. As noted above, subscription warrants=
 could be issued for no consideration=C2=A0and have negligible value. The v=
alue of a subscription warrant, if any, would appear to derive primarily fr=
om expectations that the sponsor ultimately will offer holders the ability =
to exercise the warrant on attractive terms once a target company is identi=
fied and an acquisition agreement signed. The Exchange does not address, am=
ong other things, the types of market information that could create a posit=
ive value for subscription warrants, the reliability and availability of su=
ch information, or whether such information could support fair and efficien=
t trading of an Exchange-listed security for a period as long as ten years.=
The Exchange also does not explain how it would effectively address the ris=
k the price of subscription warrants could be manipulated, or how its propo=
sal otherwise would be designed to prevent fraudulent and manipulative acts=
 and practices. For example, the price of subscription warrants would appea=
r to be particularly susceptible to rumors about potential acquisition targ=
ets and the terms of potential transactions. Because subscription warrants =
may trade at a very low price, they may permit a bad actor to efficiently m=
anipulate these securities with little upfront cost. The Exchange does not =
address how its proposal is designed to prevent the risk that subscription =
warrants may be particularly susceptible to manipulation.NYSE=E2=80=99s pro=
posed rules involve a minimum market capitalization (after listing) for the=
 warrants of $15 million; basically if they trade at a penny they have to g=
et delisted. I should say that Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s most recent SPAC, Pers=
hing Square Tontine Holdings Ltd., back when it was looking for a deal, gen=
erally traded at prices of like 15% to 25% above its cash value, suggesting=
 (by subtracting $10) a value for Ackman-affiliated SPARC warrants of $1.50=
 to $2.50.[5] (It found a deal,  the deal fell apart, and now the SPAC is p=
retty sleepy and trading a bit below cash value.)Also I should say that bas=
ically every regular SPAC=C2=A0comes with warrants:=C2=A0SPACs as a matter =
of course issue warrants to buy their stock at $11.50 per share in the even=
t of a successful deal, and those warrants trade publicly as the SPAC looks=
 for a deal, and there is not much =E2=80=9Cto prevent the risk that=E2=80=
=9D those =E2=80=9Cwarrants may be particularly susceptible to manipulation=
.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Still. The basic bet of a SPAC is =E2=80=9Cwill this sponso=
r find a good deal that I want to buy,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and that is hard to va=
lue and full of uncertainty. Tying it to a stable claim on $10 makes the co=
mbined security=C2=A0feel=C2=A0less uncertain: It=E2=80=99s mostly $10, plu=
s some guesswork. That=E2=80=99s a thing that the SEC doesn=E2=80=99t mind.=
 If you take away the $10 you are left with only the guesswork, which makes=
 the SEC nervous.
