      Who controls the FDIC?
   =20
 =20
The way a number of U.S. regulatory agencies work is that there is a profes=
sional career staff, who do the work of the agency, and there is a politica=
lly appointed chair, who is appointed by the president and is the boss of t=
he staff and=C2=A0runs the agency and sets its regulatory agenda. But there=
 are also often=C2=A0some other commissioners or board members who are ther=
e to vote on the agency=E2=80=99s big decisions.[6] Often there are about f=
our of those people, and about two will be Democrats and two will be Republ=
icans, and the chair will also be partisan and will break ties. And the job=
 of the majority-party commissioners or board members is to vote to approve=
 new rules and actions that the chair wants, and the job of the minority-pa=
rty commissioners is to write zingy dissents and tweet and give speeches ab=
out how the agency has run wild by over- or under-regulating, depending on =
which party is in the majority.The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.=C2=A0is =
in a weird place right now[7] in that:=09Its chair, Jelena McWilliams, is a=
 Republican,  appointed by Donald Trump to a five-year term in 2018,[8] but=
=09The other four seats on  the board of directors=C2=A0include one vacancy=
 and three Democrats.So the Democrats are the=C2=A0majority=C2=A0party on t=
he board, but the=C2=A0chair=C2=A0is a Republican. The ordinary procedure i=
s that the chair sets the agenda for the agency=C2=A0and then the board vot=
es on it. In this situation you might expect that to produce a lot of inact=
ion =E2=80=94=C2=A0the chair proposes to do stuff, and the majority of the =
board votes it down =E2=80=94=C2=A0which I suppose is more or less what a R=
epublican bank regulator would want anyway.But here the Democratic majority=
 members want to do stuff, but not the stuff the Republican chair wants to =
do, so they have proposed their own agenda. And she has ignored it, and the=
 FDIC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0general counsel =E2=80=94 who was appointed by the cha=
ir in 2019=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0has opined that she=E2=80=99s entitled to ig=
nore it. They would win a vote, but they can=E2=80=99t vote for the things =
they want, because she decides what they vote on.=C2=A0And so the Democrats=
 have held their own little meeting to advance their agenda with a majority=
 of the vote, and the chair has said that their meeting doesn=E2=80=99t cou=
nt, and the general counsel has agreed with her:A partisan fight atop a sle=
epy bank regulator intensified on Tuesday, with Democratic members of the F=
ederal Deposit Insurance Corporation board saying its Republican chairwoman=
 was subverting the majority=E2=80=99s will.Rohit Chopra, a member of the F=
.D.I.C. board and the new director of the Consumer Financial Protection Bur=
eau, complained that the chairwoman, Jelena McWilliams =E2=80=94 a Trump ap=
pointee =E2=80=94 had refused to recognize their attempts to review rules a=
bout bank mergers.=E2=80=9CThis approach to governance is unsafe and unsoun=
d,=E2=80=9D he said in a statement. =E2=80=9CIt is also an attack on the ru=
le of law.=E2=80=9DAt a virtual meeting earlier Tuesday, Ms. McWilliams, th=
e board=E2=80=99s lone Republican, struck down Mr. Chopra=E2=80=99s request=
 to record in the minutes a vote on the review. Ms. McWilliams said the reg=
ulator=E2=80=99s general counsel had ruled the vote, which had been taken e=
arlier by the Democratic members, to be invalid.One of the Democratic board=
 members, Rohit Chopra, is also the director of the Consumer Financial Prot=
ection Bureau, and he took to=C2=A0his agency=E2=80=99s website to complain=
:Since joining the Board in October, there have been a number of concerning=
 representations made by certain Corporation officers about board governanc=
e. In my board member orientation, I was informed that it was the view of t=
he Board=E2=80=99s General Counsel that board members may not raise matters=
 for discussion in board meetings, and only the Chairperson has this right.=
 Although the Corporation=E2=80=99s bylaws specifically authorize two board=
 members to call for special meetings, the General Counsel has taken the pe=
rplexing view that those board members cannot guarantee that any topics wil=
l actually be discussed.In late October, my fellow Directors and I circulat=
ed a draft Request for Information on the Bank Merger Act with the intentio=
n of releasing it jointly with the Office of the Comptroller of the Currenc=
y. This was not a draft rule or guidance document =E2=80=93 it was largely =
a series of questions to solicit input, given the President=E2=80=99s reaso=
nable request, the need to incorporate the Dodd-Frank Act=E2=80=99s amendme=
nts, and the long-term trend in consolidation. This should have been a no-b=
rainer where consensus could easily be achieved. But because of the General=
 Counsel=E2=80=99s improper assertion that the Chairperson had implicit vet=
o power, the draft was not given appropriate attention. Directors Gruenberg=
, Hsu, and I waited for feedback, but to no avail.I am not an expert in the=
 bylaws of the FDIC so I don=E2=80=99t know who will win. In general I agre=
e with Chopra=E2=80=99s view that it is very bad governance if the majority=
 of a board cannot make decisions because the chair has unreviewable contro=
l over the agenda. On the other hand I take the general counsel=E2=80=99s p=
oint that,=C2=A0usually, the chair of an agency runs the agency and the boa=
rd just votes on stuff she proposes.=C2=A0Previously we  discussed a power =
struggle at the top of the CFPB early in the Trump administration, when the=
re were two competing claimants to the title of CFPB director (one appointe=
d by Trump, one not) and they fought it out in court and ultimately Trump=
=E2=80=99s appointee took over. One thing that helped him, I argued, was br=
inging doughnuts. (Not to court, I mean; to the CFPB.) =E2=80=9CThe CFPB=C2=
=A0is in a weird place right now,=E2=80=9D  I wrote, =E2=80=9Cand a few wel=
l-timed breakfast pastries can probably go a long way.=E2=80=9DI am not sur=
e that quite works here? But maybe it=E2=80=99s worth a shot? The Democrati=
c board members can quietly walk the halls of the FDIC, saying to staff =E2=
=80=9Clook, eventually President Biden is going to get to appoint a Democra=
tic chair, so you might as well start working on the rules we want and stop=
 listening to your official boss, also have a doughnut.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
