      Oops
   =20
 =20
What=C2=A0is=C2=A0the right trade here?Two pals from Bolton have been jaile=
d after attempting to claim a =C2=A34 million scratch card win.Mark Goodram=
 and Jon Watson both admitted to using someone else's card details to buy t=
he winning scratch card from a Waitrose store in the Clapham area of London=
. =E2=80=A6Their jackpot joy soon turned to despair as Camelot - the compan=
y that operates The National Lottery - uncovered their fraud.Watson, 34, ex=
citedly rang Camelot, before passing the phone to Goodram. An operator aske=
d for his bank details so that the money could be transferred but when the =
38-year-old let slip that he did not have an account, it raised suspicions =
about how the scratch card was bought. =E2=80=A6Camelot's investigation was=
 eventually passed to the police when they found that the scratch card had =
been bought fraudulently, using card details belonging to a man named Joshu=
a Addiman. ...Along with the winning scratch card, the pair also used the d=
etails to buy four other scratch cards and other items totalling =C2=A371.7=
8, from Waitrose.Definitely not legal advice but! I think if you find yours=
elf in this situation the move is to call up Addiman and be like: =E2=80=9C=
Look. We stole your debit=C2=A0card. Sorry about that. But the good news is=
 that we have a winning lottery ticket that is worth 4 million pounds and w=
e=E2=80=99ll sell it to you for 2 million plus a signed release saying we h=
ad permission to use your card.=C2=A0How about it?=E2=80=9D As I type it I =
realize it does not seem especially plausible. =E2=80=9CBut the good news i=
s you=E2=80=99re gonna get a call from Camelot in a few days asking if we h=
ad permission to use your card, and if you say yes we=E2=80=99ll give you 2=
 million pounds=E2=80=9D? Still seems scammy. Either way there=E2=80=99s a =
ton of credit risk =E2=80=94=C2=A0you take his credit in the first case, he=
 takes yours in the second =E2=80=94=C2=A0because no one gets the money unt=
il you=E2=80=99ve all got your stories straight.The result here is that the=
y went to jail but also no one got the money:Mr Addiman received the fraudu=
lently-spent money back from his bank, the court heard.I am sure he was hap=
py to get back the 71.78 pounds but he=E2=80=99d prefer the 4 million. They=
 really should have worked this out.
