 call option to buy stock at a fixed price, issued by the issuer of the sto=
ck=E2=80=9D; Ackman=E2=80=99s filings refers to the rights here as both =E2=
=80=9Cspecial purpose acquisition rights, or =E2=80=98SPARs=E2=80=99=E2=80=
=9D and as =E2=80=9Csubscription warrants.=E2=80=9D[4] Actually the way Ack=
man=E2=80=99s SPARC is set up, it is the right to pay $10 *or more* for a s=
hare of the company: The exercise price of the SPARC warrant has to be at l=
east $10, but if Ackman wants to raise more capital for a deal he can incre=
ase the exercise price.[5] Annoyingly PSTH has a cash value of $20 per shar=
e, so I can=E2=80=99t just say it traded at $11.50 to $12.50 =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0it traded at $23 to $25. But you can divide by two; that=E2=80=99s also =
easy arithmetic.[6] There are constitutional and administrative-law reasons=
 for this that are deathly boring so I will not get into them. The short ve=
rsion is that it is constitutionally magical to have a regulatory agency ru=
n by a five-person board instead of by one person.[7] Also the FDIC is a bi=
t unusual in that two of its board members are the Comptroller of the Curre=
ncy and the director of the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau. So their =
day job is not writing snarky dissents and tweets about FDIC decisions, but=
 rather running the CFPB or the OCC.[8] A six-year term on the FDIC board, =
but five years as chair, which is what matters here.
