und-color: #ccc;"> Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s proposal to do a SPARC</a>, a spec=
ial purpose acquisition=C2=A0<em>rights=C2=A0</em>company. A SPARC is like =
a SPAC except that instead of paying $10 for a share of a SPAC, you pay $0 =
for a =E2=80=9Cright=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwarrant=E2=80=9D of the SPARC.[3]=
 A SPARC warrant initially represents:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: dec=
imal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">The right to pay $10 to buy a share of some company to be named later.=
[4]</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, the SPARC consists of (1=
) a SPAC=C2=A0<em>minus=C2=A0</em>(2) $10. In a SPAC, you put $10 in a pot =
and might later be asked to use it to buy a company, but you can say no and=
 take your money back.=C2=A0In a SPARC, you might later be asked to put in =
$10 to buy a company, but you can say no and keep your money.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are very tidy-minded, as I am, you will be temp=
ted to say =E2=80=9Cwell this is exactly the same as a SPAC, except minus $=
10.=E2=80=9D Ten dollars is, as a financial quantity goes, quite straightfo=
rward and tractable. You can probably figure out how to subtract $10. In ge=
neral, if I said to you =E2=80=9CAsset X is worth an amount of money that d=
epends on a complex formula and a series of assumptions about cash flows an=
d market psychology and managerial prowess, and Asset Y is worth the same a=
s Asset X minus $10,=E2=80=9D you would not think that Asset Y is any=C2=A0=
<em>harder=C2=A0</em>to value than Asset X. If you can do X, you can do Y. =
That subtraction is easy. Taking out the $10 makes no theoretical differenc=
e.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But much of the work of finance consists=
 of doing things that make no theoretical difference because they have some=
 practical advantage, and Ackman is very keen on his SPARC idea. (I am too;=
 I think it=E2=80=99s fun.) A big advantage of the SPARC is that, if you=E2=
=80=99re a SPARC investor,=C2=A0<em>you get to keep your money:=C2=A0</em>Y=
ou only put up the $10 when Ackman finds a company to buy, rather than putt=
ing it in a pot while he looks for one. There are also legal advantages tha=
t make the SPARC a bit more flexible than a SPAC: Ackman would have more ti=
me to find a company, and he=E2=80=99d be able to raise a variable amount o=
f money with the SPARC rather than just the fixed amount in a SPAC pool.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also it seems to me that the SPARC is in an i=
mportant sense <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/260=
53246.265643/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMj=
EtMDYtMDQvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4tcy1zcGFjLXdpbGwtYmUtdGhyZWUtc3BhY3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEM=
TIxNTIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXIm=
dXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMjE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cCbd8c35a5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> more honest than a SPAC</a>. The way a SPAC works is =
that it has some money in its pool, and the SPAC sponsor goes to a private =
company and says =E2=80=9Chey I can take you public and give you this $300 =
million=E2=80=9D or whatever, and they agree on a deal, and then they annou=
nce it, and then the SPAC shareholders can withdraw their money if they wan=
t and the target company might get nothing. (See, e.g., <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26053246.265643/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqL=
mNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9idXp6ZmVlZC1zdWZmZXJzLXdhdmUtb2Ytc3BhYy1pbnZlc3Rvci13aXRo=
ZHJhd2Fscy1iZWZvcmUtZ29pbmctcHVibGljLTExNjM4NDcyNzU2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBaa07763a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">BuzzFeed Inc.</a>) The way a SPARC works is that Bill =
Ackman goes to a private company and says =E2=80=9Chey I think if we play o=
ur cards right I can take you public and raise $3 billion for you=E2=80=9D =
or whatever, and if they agree on a deal it=E2=80=99s because the company b=
elieves in Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s ability to raise the money, not because th=
e company is distracted by the money already being there. In a SPAC the mon=
ey is already there, but that=E2=80=99s an illusion; it can vanish. In a SP=
ARC it is clearer that the money will come only if the deal is good and Bil=
l Ackman=E2=80=99s fans believe in it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On t=
he other hand you might object that subtracting $10 from a SPAC makes the S=
PARC=C2=A0<em>worse=C2=A0</em>in some substantive way. In particular, these=
 days, there are a lot of SPACs chasing not that many deals, a lot of SPAC =
investors ask for their money back when deals are announced, and so a lot o=
f SPACs trade at around $10 or a little less =E2=80=94=C2=A0$9.97 or whatev=
er =E2=80=94=C2=A0because they are effectively a weird way to get back $10 =
in a few months. In other words, the right to buy a share of a stock to be =
named later is worthless, and the SPAC share consists=C2=A0<em>only=C2=A0</=
em>of the claim on $10.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How does that work =
with a SPARC? The right can=E2=80=99t trade=C2=A0<em>below=C2=A0</em>zero, =
and even trading=C2=A0<em>at=C2=A0</em>zero =E2=80=94=C2=A0for a SPARC acti=
vely looking for a company =E2=80=94=C2=A0would be weird; surely there is=
=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>option value there. Maybe it=E2=80=99s worth a pen=
ny or two. But =E2=80=9Cmaybe a penny or two=E2=80=9D is a pretty bad price=
 for a publicly traded security, much much worse than =E2=80=9Cmaybe 10 buc=
ks more or less.=E2=80=9D Subtracting $10 from the SPAC price, if the SPAC =
price is roughly $10, results in madness.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A=
ckman and the New York Stock Exchange (which wants to list his SPARC) need =
the Securities and Exchange Commission to approve the idea, and the SEC see=
ms unhappy. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/260532=
46.265643/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaW5zdGl0dXRpb25hbGludmVzdG9yLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlL2Ixd=
ncxcng2c3BucnRyL0JpbGwtQWNrbWFuLUdldHMtTW9yZS1QdXNoYmFjay1Gcm9tLXRoZS1TRUM/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB197dd9c0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Michelle Celarier reports</a>:</=
p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Comm=
ission is pushing back against hedge fund manager Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s eff=
ort to create a new-fangled security called a SPARC, or special purpose acq=
uisition rights company. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead =
of either approving the security or turning it down as expected, however, t=
he SEC asked for more time =E2=80=94 and more information =E2=80=94 before =
making its decision. In a 17-page release, the regulator said that it is wo=
rried about the new security=E2=80=99s potential for manipulation in part b=
ecause of comment letters it received from three people, one of whom was an=
onymous. The vast majority of the comments on the new security, which was p=
ut forth by the New York Stock Exchange, were supportive. But the SEC is as=
king for more details from the NYSE on how its concerns will be addressed.=
=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26053246.265643/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc=
2VjLmdvdi9ydWxlcy9zcm8vbnlzZS8yMDIxLzM0LTkzNzQxLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB3f86acf6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">the SEC=E2=80=99s response</a>; here=E2=80=99s the se=
ction on the trading prices:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
e Exchange does not explain how market participants would effectively value=
 this novel listed security, or how it would be expected to trade consisten=
t with fair and orderly markets and the protection of investors and the pub=
lic interest. As noted above, subscription warrants could be issued for no =
consideration=C2=A0and have negligible value. The value of a subscription w=
arrant, if any, would appear to derive primarily from expectations that the=
 sponsor ultimately will offer holders the ability to exercise the warrant =
on attractive terms once a target company is identified and an acquisition =
agreement signed. The Exchange does not address, among other things, the ty=
pes of market information that could create a positive value for subscripti=
on warrants, the reliability and availability of such information, or wheth=
er such information could support fair and efficient trading of an Exchange=
-listed security for a period as long as ten years.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">The Exchange also does not explain how it would effectively addres=
s the risk the price of subscription warrants could be manipulated, or how =
its proposal otherwise would be designed to prevent fraudulent and manipula=
tive acts and practices. For example, the price of subscription warrants wo=
uld appear to be particularly susceptible to rumors about potential acquisi=
tion targets and the terms of potential transactions. Because subscription =
warrants may trade at a very low price, they may permit a bad actor to effi=
ciently manipulate these securities with little upfront cost. The Exchange =
does not address how its proposal is designed to prevent the risk that subs=
cription warrants may be particularly susceptible to manipulation.</p></blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">NYSE=E2=80=99s proposed rules involve =
a minimum market capitalization (after listing) for the warrants of $15 mil=
lion; basically if they trade at a penny they have to get delisted. I shoul=
d say that Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s most recent SPAC, Pershing Square Tontine =
Holdings Ltd., back when it was looking for a deal, generally traded at pri=
ces of like 15% to 25% above its cash value, suggesting (by subtracting $10=
) a value for Ackman-affiliated SPARC warrants of $1.50 to $2.50.[5] (It fo=
und a deal, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/260532=
46.265643/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtM=
DctMjAvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4tcy10aHJlZS1zcGFjcy13ZXJlLXRvby1tYW55P2NtcGlkPUJCRDEy=
MTUyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV=
0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTIxNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cBaef6d116" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> the deal fell apart</a>, and now the SPAC is pretty sl=
eepy and trading a bit below cash value.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A=
lso I should say that basically every regular SPAC<em>=C2=A0comes with warr=
ants:=C2=A0</em>SPACs as a matter of course issue warrants to buy their sto=
ck at $11.50 per share in the event of a successful deal, and those warrant=
s trade publicly as the SPAC looks for a deal, and there is not much =E2=80=
=9Cto prevent the risk that=E2=80=9D <em>those </em>=E2=80=9Cwarrants may b=
e particularly susceptible to manipulation.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Still. The basic bet of a SPAC is =E2=80=9Cwill this sponso=
r find a good deal that I want to buy,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and that is hard to va=
lue and full of uncertainty. Tying it to a stable claim on $10 makes the co=
mbined security=C2=A0<em>feel=C2=A0</em>less uncertain: It=E2=80=99s mostly=
 $10, plus some guesswork. That=E2=80=99s a thing that the SEC doesn=E2=80=
=99t mind. If you take away the $10 you are left with only the guesswork, w=
hich makes the SEC nervous.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=
